('101', '7', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Uyghurs, Kazakhs and other predominantly Turkic Muslim peoples living in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region (XUAR) in China have long faced government-directed discrimination and persecution. In 2017, under the guise of a campaign to counter the ‘three evil forces’ of terrorism, extremism, and separatism, the government commenced a massive escalation of it abuses against these peoples. The campaign’s actual objectives are to eradicate Islamic religious beliefs and Turkic Muslim ethno-cultural practices, and to replace these with other secular, state-sanctioned, views and activities, and ultimately to ‘transform’ members of ethnic minorities in Xinjiang into obedient supporters of the Chinese Communist Party and President Xi Jinping.\r\n\r\nTo achieve this cultural erasure and political indoctrination, the government enacted far-reaching policies that violate the fundamental human rights and commenced a campaign of mass-arrest, mass-incarceration, and torture. More than a million men and women – Uyghurs, Kazakhs, Kyrgyz, Uzbeks, Tatars, Tajiks, and Dungans – have been arbitrarily arrested, denied due process, and unlawfully interned in so-called ‘re-education camps’ (that is, internment camps), where they were subjected to a ceaseless indoctrination campaign as well as physical and psychological torture and other forms of ill-treatment.\r\n\r\nThe whereabouts of many of the men and women sent to internment camps are not known. Hundreds of thousands have been transferred to situations of forced labour or given long sentences and sent to prison. Many remain in indefinite incommunicado detention in the internment camps. Those who have been permitted to return to their homes are placed under strict conditions – well beyond those already imposed on all members of minority groups – limiting their behaviors, movements, associations.\r\n\r\nThe brutal effectiveness and tremendous scale of the government’s campaign derives from its unprecedented use of surveillance technology coupled with its ability to mobilize huge portions of the population to enforce its will. The campaign relies on a nearly inescapable in-person and electronic surveillance operation designed to ensure that the behavior of ethnic monitories is continuously monitored and evaluated. Ubiquitous government cadres, violent security forces, and a subservient legal system act in concert – along with a substantial portion of the civilian population who have been terrorized into complicity – to conduct the surveillance operation, enforce the illegal policies, and administer internment camps system.  As a result, members of the targeted ethnic groups – including those who have never been sent to an internment camp, a prison, or a situation of forced labour –  currently live in fear, under the constant and highly credible threat of arrest, detention, torture, and disappearance, under a draconian system of social control that is a constant affront to basic human dignity.\r\n\r\nThis report details human rights violations committed by the government of China in Xinjiang between 2017 and 2020. The findings are based primarily on first-hand testimonial evidence from XX survivors and witnesses interviewed by Amnesty International, XX of whom had never shared their stories publicly before. The report also draws on leaked government documents and a substantial body of public reporting by journalists and investigators. The report has five main chapters.\r\n\r\nChapter one describes human rights violations in Xinjiang that occur outside of the camps.  Government policies heavily restrict the basic rights and freedoms of members of ethnic minorities in Xinjiang. Chapter two focuses on what happens to detainees from the time they are arrested until they enter an internment camps, the process of arrest, detention, interrogation, biometric data collection, and transfer to the camps. Chapter three details life for detainees inside the internment camps, including the conditions in the camps, the highly-regimented daily routines, the content of the ‘re-education’ curriculum, and the widespread and systematic use of torture and other forms of ill-treatment. It also provides information about the structure and scale of the internment camp system and, using satellite imagery, it provides estimates of the number, size, and location of camps that remain operational. Chapter four examines what happens to many detainees after they are released from internment camps, including ‘conditional release’, ‘camp to labour’, and ‘camp to prison’. Chapter five describes the restriction on the rights and freedoms experienced by ex-internees and their families after they are released from the camps, including the surveillance by government ‘minders’ who often life with the ex-detainees, other restriction on movement and association, continued ‘re-education’ classes, and social ostracization.\r\n\r\nThe evidence collected by Amnesty International demonstrates that the Government of China knowingly and purposefully targeted ethnic minority group in Xinjiang, including by unlawful restrictions of their basic human rights, as well as by an ethnically-targeted campaign of mass-arrest, mass-incarceration, and torture and other ill treatment. The government’s actions evince a clear intent to target certain populations collectively on the basis of their ethnicity and religion and to use serious violence and intimidation to outlaw their religious practices and eradicate their ethno-cultural identify.  On the basis of the evidence gathered by Amnesty International and from other sources that Amnesty has concluded to be credible, this report concludes that the government of China has committed serious violations of international human rights law and international criminal law, including crimes against humanity.'),
