('161', '15', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', '<blockquote>“The trainee\'s study, life, and activity management system should be formulated in detail, and the students should have a fixed bed position, fixed queue position, fixed classroom seat, and fixed station during skills work, and it is strictly forbidden for this to be changed. Strengthen the student\'s daily life behavior norms, and implement behavioral norms and discipline requirements for getting up, rollcall, washing, going to the toilet, organizing and housekeeping, eating, studying, sleeping, closing the door and so forth. Increase the discipline and punishment of behavioral violations, and form a serious, standardized and orderly study and living order.”\r\n– Classified Chinese government document (the ‘telegram’) describing ‘behaviour management’ for people in internment camps in Xinjiang.</blockquote>\r\nAmnesty international interviewed XX survivors of Chinese internment camps in Xinjiang. XX of whom had never been interviewed publicly before, and X of whom had never shared certain parts of their story publicly. These testimonies add to the substantial body of testimonial evidence – from XX other survivors – gathered by journalists, human rights investigators, activists, and diaspora organizations. Each interviewee shared an in-depth account of the their experience in the camps. Nearly all survivors interviewed by Amnesty were in the camps for at least a year. The vast majority of the testimonies reveal a broadly similar description of life in the internment camps system.\r\n\r\nInternees almost always arrived at the camp handcuffed, and often hooded and shackled. Upon arrival, they were searched, their personal effects were confiscated, and that they were made to remove certain items of clothing, including shoelaces, belt, buttons or anything else that could be used as a weapon or a implement to commit suicide with. Most were then given uniforms and taken to their cell. Women internees reported that their hair was cut after arriving in the camps. Religious men had their heads shaved. Many detainees reported being terrified when they arrived at the camps. “As soon as the police handed me over [to the camp guards] it was scary. There were many guards with weapons and electric batons,” [Pseudonym L1] told Amnesty International.\r\n\r\nShortly after arriving in the camp, all detainees are brought to the room where they spend the majority of their time – their cell. Cells in internment camps are basic rooms, which usually hold about fifteen to twenty people. The cell normally consists of bunkbeds and small stools or chairs. Most internees had their own bed, but some said that they share a bed. There is usually a TV in the cell. And often a Chinese flag on the wall. The door to the cell is chained to the wall. [Pseudonym X13] told Amnesty International how humiliating it was to go under the chain.“The door is just half open. It was chained to the wall. We had to crawl under the chain one by one, like dogs,” he said.\r\n\r\nCell doors often have two ‘holes’; one for the guards stationed in the hallway outside to look in and another to pass food through. There are several CCTV cameras – usually four – in the cell. Survivors stated that the cells were position in such way that you could not see any other rooms from your door. There is usually a loudspeaker in the room, through which camp staff speak to detainees. Detainees are largely forbidden from speaking to each other in their cells. Some said they were forbidden from looking outside. Guards are stationed outside the cell.\r\n\r\nInternees were generally forbidden from speaking with each other. And at all times, internees are forbidden from speaking any language other than Mandarin, which many internees – especially older ones – did not know how to speak.'),
