('289', '9', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'The government of China has taken extraordinary measures to prevent accurate information about the situation in Xinjiang from being documented. Chinese citizens – particularly internment camp survivors –  have been effectively prevented from speaking about or otherwise sharing information about the situation in Xinjiang. The possibility of speaking from Xinjiang over a genuinely secure form of communication from is remote and the consequences of being identified are severe. All members of ethnic minority groups in Xinjiang are under some form of surveillance. And anyone who does speak out about the internment camps – or is perceived to have spoken out -- or is accused of speaking out – risks arrest, detention, imprisonment, torture, and disappearance, not only for themselves but also for their family members.\r\n\r\nThe risks are even more severe for ex-detainees and their families, who already face heightened levels of suspicion and surveillance. For at least several months after being released all ex-internees are under near constant electronic and in-person surveillance. Everyone who is released from an internment camp signs a document that forbids them from speaking with anybody – especially journalists and foreigners – about what they experienced in the camp, and specifies that if they violate this prohibition that they will be interned again, along with members of their family.\r\n\r\nAS a result of the obstacles and risks facing people in Xinjiang, with few exceptions, the vast majority of credible testimonial evidence about the situation has been gathered from survivors and witnesses who have left Xinjiang and spoken from abroad. Speaking from abroad is also difficult and comes with serious risk. Since 2017, obtaining permission to travel abroad – or, in some cases, domestically – has been nearly impossible for Uyghurs, and extraordinarily difficult for all other Turkic Muslims. Members of ethnic minority groups who have obtained permission to travel abroad since 2017 appear to require a strong connection to foreign country (usually citizenship or immediate family) and one or more ‘guarantors’ who agree, in writing, that they will be sent to a camp if the person they were guaranteeing speaks or shared information about the internment camps or does not return to China on time. As documented in this report and elsewhere, these are not empty threats; family members of people who speak about the issue from abroad have been sent to internment camps and in some cases disappeared.\r\n\r\nIndependent journalists and human rights investigators have all been denied ‘real’ access to the region. Those who have travelled to the region have encountered a coordinated effort by government officials to blocked them from speaking with survivors and witnesses and from accessing internment camps, except in situations where the government exercises complete control over where they visit, who they speak with, and what is said to them. Reporting about the situation from abroad also carries significant risk. In several instances, when journalists with family in Xinjiang have reported on or spoken out about the situation in Xinjiang from abroad, members of their family have been arrested, sent to a camp or prison, or disappeared.\r\n\r\nThere has also been a concerted effort by Chinese government officials to provide misinformation and disinformation, both to foreigners and to the local population. Several internment camp survivors told Amnesty that they were also forced to give false statements to their families or to the media while interned and after they had been released.[[[B2, z1]]] Several internment camp survivors told Amnesty International that while they were interned they had been coached about what to say to foreign journalists or Chinese government delegations that visited their camp.[[[Q1, I2, y2 – made to sing and dance]]][[[I2]]]  [Pseudonym Q1] told, who spent a year[[[check]]] in internment camp, told Amnesty International how he was trained to speak with journalist who were supposed to come to the camp he was in.\r\n<blockquote>“One day they told us journalists were coming. And that when you see them to smile. And to say what you were told or you will be taken to underground room…. [During the days before the journalists were scheduled to arrive] Our Chinese language classes stopped. And we practiced answering questions for journalists, for more than ten days… we practiced saying that the food is good and the Chinese Communist Party is great. I don’t know if the journalists ever came because we were not allowed to go out. I heard they came, but I didn’t see them.”[[[Q1]]</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym X2], who spent more than a year in multiple internment camps, told Amnesty shat she was part of group that coached for twenty days about what to say to visiting journalists. “[We were coached] to say that we were studying well, deepening our knowledge, and we are thankful to the state, are getting a salary, that our family is taken care of, that we are here for the daytime only, and here voluntarily,” she said.\r\n\r\nRecent ‘leaked’ government documents obtained by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ), the New York Times, and other media outlets and scholars appear to have triggered attempt at even tighter controls on information coming out of Xinjiang, including through the physical destruction of documents related to the internment camp systems.  Amnesty International received several account of government cadres being made to burn files related to the internment camp system in aftermath of the leaks. One camp survivor, and former government cadre, told Amnesty International that he participated in burning files. “I attended the burning. It was in … 2019, after I was released …I was helping to carry the files. …  it took five or six days to burn everything [in the office],” he said.\r\n\r\nThe government’s attempts to silence the affected population and destroy the evidence echoes a directive from one of the leaked government document obtained by the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists – known as the ‘telegram’ -- which emphasizes the importance of maintaining ‘strict secrecy’ with respect to everything that happens inside camps.  While the leaked portion of the directive lacks significant details about how the secrecy will be maintained beyond the statement that “[i]t is necessary to strengthen the [internment camps’] staff’s awareness of staying secret, serious political discipline and secrecy discipline,” the experiences of survivors and witnesses documented in this report and elsewhere illustrate the immense resources that have been devoted to this cover-up effort as well as the (often violent) methods used ensure the silence of the civilian population.'),
