('479', '28', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Prior to being sent to a camp, nearly all detainees were subjected to a medical examination. [Pseudonym X2], a camp survivor who worked at a hospital where some people were examined before they sent to the camps, witnessed part of the medical examination process.\r\n<blockquote>“In the [the city I lived in] there were four hospitals – infection, military, traditional, and regular – in 2017 they all started being used for people sent to re-education camps. … At first it was Uyghurs and Dungans. They were simple people, but police treated them as serious criminals. There were six guards per person [brought for a medical examination]. Their eyes were covered, hooded, and their hands were cuffed [when they arrived at the hospital]. The whole medical examination was top secret. …  [The staff at the hospital] had to make sure they were healthy. [The staff] had to draw their blood to make sure they were healthy. … They were all young. I was there helping with [redacted]. … The targets were young graduates. [At the time, at the hospital I worked at it was] mainly Dungans who studied [abroad].”</blockquote>\r\nIn addition to medical exams, all survivors told Amnesty International that they were required to surrender their biometric data, including having their photo taken, iris scan, voice recordings, and writing samples. Biometric data was often collected at police stations.  Several survivors told believe they took their DNA. “Then we went to a police station for what I think was a DNA exam. … They took our blood, spread it on something, and put it in a plastic wrap,” [Pseudonym X2] told Amnesty international when describing when she arrested.\r\n\r\nThe health checks and biometric data collection is consistent with other survivor accounts reported elsewhere. And with reports of widespread campaigns for biometric data collection from all people in Xinjiang, not just those sent to the camps.\r\n\r\nAfter the medical exams and biometric data collection was complete, the arrestees were transferred to camps. Numerous survivors told Amnesty International that they were hooded and handcuffed when they were transferred to a camp, or that they witnesses people hooded and handcuffed people being transported to a camp. [Pseudonym B2], who was arrested for visiting Kazakhstan told Amnesty International about being transferred to the camp. “They came in the morning. The police entered our cell [in the police station]. They put a black hood [on me]. Handcuffed me. And dragged me to the bus. And then took us to the camp,” he said.'),
