('629', '101', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'The majority of survivors reported never being allowed outside during their detention, except when walking from their cell to their class if it was in another building. A minority of detainees reported being given a short amount of time outside each day. Several survivors report not being allowed out at all for the first few months in the camps, and then being given a couple minutes a day during the remainder of their internment. A guard who worked at the camp said new detainees were not allowed outside during the first three months of their detention, then allowed a half hour/day.  Some survivors reported being given time outside every couple of weeks.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym E2] told Amnesty how he was not permitted outside at all during the first half of his year-long detention, but in the second half was permitted some time.\r\n<blockquote>“[For the first 6 months] We never saw sunlight. We were always in cell. Only during interrogations [did we leave our cell]. One corner of cell has [a window], but it is covered by a dark net. You can see a bit of the sky. … We sit still all day. We ate food was in our cell. … The beds were in one room. Then were was another door beside the toilet, [which goes to a small area] with fresh air. There was a metal net [over this area]. We had 1hr/day in this [outside enclosure]. … before 2018 we would sit still all day. After 2018 we would sit still and then be allowed into that area.”</blockquote>\r\nFor internees who did walk to class in another building, it was often the only time that detainees got to walk or leave their rooms during the day. “The second camp was worse because there was no walk to class [the class was in our room], so we were never outside,” [Pseudonym] said. A few survivors said that the only time there were ever outside was to throw out the bucket the he and he cell mates urinated in.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym B2], who was sent to the camp because had WhatsApp on her phone told Amnesty how she was never able to get any exercise or have sunlight or fresh air.\r\n<blockquote>“… There is no fresh air. There is no daylight. The windows [in the cell] are blocked. … … The windows were covered by film. There is no sunlight. Only opportunity to go outside was to take the trash out. We were never outside, except at the very beginning when there were few people. Once more people arrived we never went out. … and once the number grew they stopped taking us to the canteen and brought food to our room.”</blockquote>\r\nSurvivors often reported that their room was very cold. And that there is little or no natural light.  There rooms usually have either no windows or one very small window which is often covered. “There is a metal net over the window so no finger can reach the glass. And the window is covered by communist slogan. You can’t see outside… we sat in chair the whole day from December to April… during these four months we never saw the sun,” [Pseudonym] said.'),
