('651', '102', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'At around nine or ten at night, detainees are given a few moments to wash up, use the toilet, and go to bed. Nearly all survivors reported that each night they were made to ‘work’ one or two-hour shifts monitoring their cellmates every night.   The shifts were spent either by walking continuously around the room or by sitting still on the edge of the bed.   One survivor reported that he was instructed to reposition people’s heads or lower the bedding if someone was not sleeping with their face visible and facing the camera. Several survivors claim that this policy was instituted to insure that no one is committing suicide. Several had no idea why they were ‘on-duty’.\r\n\r\nSome survivors reported being made to sleep head to toe so that people are unable to communicate with each other at night. “You can’t talk. They regulate [how we are positioned when we] sleep so that we can’t talk [to other people in the cell] – our head is [positioned] next to someone’s feet,” [Pseudonym X5] told Amnesty International.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym A4], who was arrested for allegedly failing to get permission to travel domestically, told Amnesty International how at night internees were responsible for monitoring each other and for ensuring that their faces were always visible to the CCTV cameras installed in the cell:\r\n<blockquote>“The lights [in the cell] are always only. At 10pm we had to lie in bed. Two cell mates were on night watch. From 10 to 12, 12 to 2, 2 to 4, and 4 to 6… these two people are [always] walking between the window and the door. Their job is watching us. At night we have to sleep with head facing camera and face uncovered. And if not they wake us and put us in the right position.”</blockquote>\r\nEven if you are not ‘on-duty’, it was difficult to sleep when you were not on duty because of the noise from the loudspeaker. Most survivors reported that the lights in the cell are always on, even at night.'),
