('757', '106', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Prior to the start of class, during the first few days, weeks, and sometimes months after arriving at the internment camps, many of the survivors reported that they were essentially forced to do ‘nothing’ for nearly the entire day. The only breaks were for meals or to sleep. Many complained about being forced to sit or kneel in uncomfortable positions that were very painful for their knees and other parts of their body, and that they developed hemorrhoids and other health problems. Many reported that inmates were physically punished if they were unwilling or unable to sit straight. Several reported not being permitted to look anywhere but straight ahead. According to letter from a former camp guard, inmates were not allowed to show emotion.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors reported having to sing songs or to recite the Chinese alphabet or other basic Chinese words while they sat – or in a few instances stood – still;  others we made watched Chinese propaganda films. Some literally had to ‘do nothing’ except to sit perfectly still on a small chair or stool in their room, or, in a few cases, to stand still.   “I just sat on stool for three months form morning to 11pm… there was no class, nothing,” [Pseudonym] said.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym, who was sent to the camp for visiting Kazakhstan, told Amnesty that he was in a camp for several months before they started taking him to class.\r\n<blockquote>“During the days before classes [started] we had to sit on stools [all day]. For 16 hours a day we had to sit on stools with our hands on our knees. We were up at 6am, the sit on stool, then breakfast…. Then sit until lunch. Sometimes we were given a book [to learn from]. We could not talk to other people. We had our lunch sitting on the stool. During lunch we could have a nap of an hour or less, sometimes not at all…. Then we sit again until it gets dark.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym], who was detained for visiting Kazakhstan, told Amnesty that for the first two months after he arrived at the camp, he was forced to sit still in an uncomfortable position for hours each day:\r\n<blockquote>“After breakfast we had to sit on our beds with our hands on our knees and a straight back. If we moved, they spoken to us through a loudspeaker [in the room] and said ‘don’t move’. Then around 1130/12 they brought lunch. Then from 1230-2 we could lie down [on our bed]. Then at 2pm they told us to maintain the seated position. We sat like that until dinner, but they sometimes said through loudspeaker that we had five minutes to move, lie down, or to urinate in the bucket [in the room]. … Around 7pm we had dinner, and then we watched TV [while sitting] … At 9pm they ordered us to go to bed. … We spent [the first] two months without leaving the room. [Except] during the day they took us to the toilet which was outside the room to [defecate]. They took us two times a day. … We never went outside. ”</blockquote>\r\nBased off the survivor testimony, it is unclear whether doing ‘nothing’ was a deliberate policy to demoralize/break the will/spirit or newly arrived detainees, or if it was consequence of the fact that at the start of the government campaign of mass incarceration certain camps were not set up to provide any formalized instruction at certain times. It is plausible that it was a deliberate policy in certain camps at certain times but not in others.'),
