('799', '37', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Internees are often interrogated. The manner and frequency of the interrogations appears to vary widely from camp to camp and person to person. Some survivor report being interrogated once or twice during their entire stay, others report frequent interrogations.  Like during the interrogations in police stations and detention centers (described in section X above), the interrogations focused on the internees religious practice, foreign contacts, relationship with terrorists or suspicious people. Numerous survivors reported being forced to ‘confess’ to their crime during interrogations; several survivors told Amnesty that they had done what they were being accused of (i.e. travelling abroad, downloading WhatsApp) so they considered their confession to be honest.\r\n\r\nMany interrogations took place in rooms where internees sat across a desk from government official. Many interrogations also took place in ‘punishment rooms’, which were usually in the basement of the camp.  [Pseudonym O1] who was arrested for working in Kazakhstan, told Amnesty that how he was interrogated in a room in the basement of his camp.\r\n<blockquote>“[Security agents] took me to an underground room and put legs into an iron bar. My hands were handcuffed to the chair. They asked me about my biography. Where I was born, when I started school, where did I go after high school, which did I study. I told them I went to Kazakhstan. They asked me how many times I visited and were I went, and where I stayed. They asked for the names of my relatives, and what [my relatives] did, did they pray? … they asked which cities in Kazakhstan I visited, which countries I visited. They also asked about [my siblings] … they asked ‘when you were in Kazakhstan did you learn how to pray? ”</blockquote>\r\nInternees are regularly required to engage in ‘confession’ or ‘self-criticism’ letters where they admit to their ‘crimes’ in writing. Some survivors reported having to do self-criticism once or twice during their interment, others reported that this was a weekly or biweekly activity. Several survivors reported being given a list of crimes to choose from to confess to, and that you needed to pick two. Journalists have reported that there were seventy-five types of crimes to choose from. Several survivors told Amnesty that they believed that people who chose – or were made to choose – certain rimes, particularly crimes related to religion, were given prison sentences.\r\n\r\nIn addition to confessing one’s crimes, as part of the ‘self-criticism’, internees were made to describe in writing what they did wrong, explain that as a result of the education they are receiving that they have recognized the error of their ways and that their thoughts have been ‘transformed’, express gratitude to the government for the education, and promise not to return to their old habits. [Pseudonym], who was put in a camp for having contact with people who had ‘extremist’ thoughts, said that he was forced to admit his crime and that he was told that if he didn’t not confess he would be sent to a punishment room.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym] told Amnesty how he was forced to choose two crimes from a list of seventy-five to confess to.\r\n<blockquote>“They started teaching us about seventy-five [crimes]. … We had to write our names and IDs and to choose at least two. The more the better. … What I read is that it is crime not to drink and not to smoke. And that thick thread – to bind straw – if you have too much then it is a crime… you have to choose which you have… for example, if you bought too much food at once to your house… and if you visited a mosque not in your home town it is a crime… I visited a mosque in another county to attend a funeral…. So I chose two. And I put my finger print on it.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym X7] who was in the camp for a year, told Amnesty how civil-servants who lived outside the camp, and who she likened to ‘case managers’, used to come to do interrogations and what she referred to as ‘self-assessments’ and ‘confessions’, where you were required to confess to your crime, reflect on your ‘progress’, and often to disavow the Muslim religion.\r\n<blockquote>“At the beginning [the civil servants] tell you your crime – [one of mine was] having WhatsApp [and travelling to Kazakhstan] – then you have to write: ‘I didn’t know having WhatsApp was a crime. I didn’t know it caused damage to CPP. Because of WhatsApp my mind was ‘compromised’. Now, after this education, I am getting better. I will not have WhatsApp on my phone again. … [My other crime was going to Kazakhstan. I had to write:] I was in Kazakhstan. I got infected by ‘ideas’. Now I will do better and get rid of ideas. … And [we also have to write] we have mistakenly chosen the religion of Islam. We will not choose this religion again. … And there was also a list of ‘misdoings’ of Muslim believers against China. For example, praying before bed. So you would have to write that you were sorry for this and that you would not do it again.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym X7] told Amnesty International that she was required to do a ‘self-assessment’ once a week. “It was the same every week, except that you must acknowledge some progress, like learning mandarin”, she said.'),
