('1191', '123', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'As a result of the government’s efforts to prevent information about the camps from becoming public, the number of internment camps that are still operational and the number of people who remain in camps is unknown. In July 2019, the government claimed that all of the camps were closed. This announcement was greeted with skepticism by journalists, scholars, and members of the diaspora.  There is credible evidence that strongly suggests that this claim is false.\r\n\r\nNo survivors who were in the camps after July 2019 have ever spoken publicly. However, thousands of people have spoken out publicly about ‘missing’ family members who were sent to the camps, and whose whereabouts are currently unknown. While is possible that it is possible that some of these missing people were released and are unable or unwilling to inform their relatives about their release, it stands to reasons that many, if not most of these missing people – and many others – are either still in camps, or have been sent to prisons or to some form of forced labour situation.\r\n\r\nSatellite imagery has shown that while some camps have closed, many are still operations and many have, in fact, been expanded since the government’s announcement.And new camps have been built as recently as X.\r\n\r\nAs of January 2021, satellite imagery by Amnesty International has revealed XXX camps that are still operational. (For an analysis of the satellite imagery in 2021 see section X below).'),
