('1213', '124', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Nearly all ex-internees reported being forced to attend classes in language and ideology after they were released.The classes usually lasted two to three hours a day and took place at night. [Pseudonym] told Amnesty International that ex-detainees were made to go every day and the other members of the village were required to go twice a week. Some family members of internees were also made to go to classes several hours a day.Several ex-detainees reported that after they were released they were required to continue to write confession and self-criticism letters and give them to local cadres.\r\n\r\nNearly all ex-internees were required to attend ‘flag raising’ every Monday morning after then were released. During the ceremony, ex-detainees were made to publicly confess their crimes, to speak out against extremism and apologize for being an extremist, and to extol the virtue of the education they had received. Several individuals told Amnesty that only ethnic minorities were required to attend the village flag raising. According to [Pseudonym M2], members of the village who were not in camps were also required to go, however, only ethnic minorities were truly compelled to attend, “Only Uyghurs go. Chinese people, they laugh at us,” she said.\r\n\r\nFamily members of internees also had to speak at flag raising ceremonies. [Pseudonym C1] told Amnesty international how his brother was made to speak about him at a flag raising ceremony.\r\n<blockquote>“Everyone Monday there is flag raising in the village office yard… relatives [of people in camps] had to stand in front of people and confess that brother had ‘disease’ and that they are ashamed and sorry. … After I was released it was better [for my family] during the [time] I was in the camp it was a nightmare. The police came to my sister’s house to check for Koran’s. They came day and night…  After I was released my sibling blame me. They are not welcoming.</blockquote>'),
