('1257', '126', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Perhaps one of the most invasive aspects of life in Xinjiang for ex-detainees is the presence of government ‘minders’. Many survivors reported that after being released from a camp government cadres were required to stay with them in their houses for several nights a month. Minders reportedly stated in the same bed. In the same bed as her.  Some reported that cadres ‘checked in’ on them during the day, but did not stay overnight. The cadres took pictures of them and their family, monitored their behaviors, and tried to teach them the correct ‘ideology’. Minders also checked the homework from the language and ideology classes. [Pseudonym X12] told Amnesty that minders would come and inspect her house every day to make sure she was home, and they would check her homework from the night school. “If you passed homework test they leave, or they would stay and help you do work,” she said.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors reported that while they were in the camp, their family members were required to have minders stay with them. [Pseudonym X13] told amnesty international how when her father was sent to a camp, she and her was forced to move back to their home village  and have government minder stay with them.  She described what the minder did while staying with the family.\r\n<blockquote>“She eats with us. Listens to what we are saying. Tells us about politics. About our crimes. For example, [she said] ‘do not go abroad. Do not contact outside world. Be thankful for government. Confess that your father committed crimes.’”</blockquote>\r\nSimilar ‘home stays’ by cadres has been widely report by journalists and other organizations.'),
