('1322', '130', '_title', 'field_602657cc293e7'),
('1323', '130', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Those individuals who do manage to go aboard are threatened if they do not return on time. Several survivors reported that government officials called them and threatened to send their family members to camp if they didn’t return or if they spoke out. [Pseudonym] told Amnesty that when he left Xinjiang he was told he would be sent to a camp if he didn’t return on time. When he didn’t return on time, police called him and said they would throw father and father-in-law in a camp if he didn’t return.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors were called by family members in Xinjiang – who were in the presence of government officials – requesting for them to return and that if they didn’t they would be sent to a camp. [Pseudonym] told Amnesty how police called him with his son and that son said that he was going to be detained if he didn’t return. Survivors told Amnesty that they believe that their family members were sent to a camp because they left the country.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym] told Amnesty how she was continually harassed by official after she arrived in Kazakhstan. “Once I came to Kazakhstan, I thought I was free…. But [government officials] kept calling. I realized that they would never let me live in peace,” she said.'),
