('1348', '51', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Crimes against humanity are prohibited action committed as part of a widespread or systematic attack directed against a civilian population pursuant to or in furtherance of a state or organizational policy.\r\n\r\nThere is significant evidence that many of the abuses documented in this report were carried out against the civilian population in Xinjiang in a widespread and systematic manner in furtherance of a state policy -- in this case as part of the government’s campaign to eradicate ‘terrorism, extremism, and separatism’. The survivor testimonies gathered by Amnesty corroborate leaked government documents and other credible testimonial, photographic, and documentary evidence collected by journalists and investigators, which, taken together, clearly illustrate that at least some of the types of serious abuses documented in this report follow a very consistent pattern of criminal conduct, and are part of well documented government policy that is knowingly and purposefully being carried out on a massive scale by government officials all over Xinjiang.\r\n\r\nMembers of the government carried out acts which meet all the objective and subjective legal elements for three crimes against humanity: (1) torture, (2) imprisonment or other severe deprivation of liberty in violation of fundamental rules of international law, and (3) persecution of an identifiable ethnic group or collectivity on ethnic grounds that are universally recognized as impermissible under international law, and (4) other inhumane acts of a similar character intentionally causing great suffering, or serious injury to body or to mental or physical health.'),
