('1588', '26', '_title', 'field_602657cc293e7'),
('1589', '26', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Since April 2017, more than a million men and women in XUAR have been arrested and sent to so-called ‘re-education camps’ (that is, internment camps). Nearly all of the arrestees have been members of predominantly Muslim ethnic minority groups -- Uyghurs, Kazakhs, Uzbeks, Tajiks, and Dungans.\r\n\r\nAmnesty International interviewed XX men and XX woman who were arrested and sent to internment camps in XUAR in 2017 and 2018. This testimonial evidence, along with other testimonial and documentary evidence gathered by journalists, scholars, and other organizations demonstrates that most – perhaps all – of the arrestees were arrested arbitrarily, for non-violent and, by all reasonable standards, lawful conduct.\r\n\r\nNearly all of the arrestees interviewed by Amnesty International were arrested without warning. Some were arrested from their houses in the middle of the night. Many were called and told to report to a police station – often under the pretense of handing in their passport – and the arrested once they arrived. Several were pressured by government officials or employers to come back from working, studying, or living abroad, and then arrested shortly after returning, often in the airport, or at the land border.\r\n\r\nAll of the arrestees were denied due process during their arrest. None were allowed access to legal counsel. None were provided with an arrest warrant or even a reason for their arrest that included a credible allegation of a known criminal offense under Chinese law or for any offense that would traditionally be considered a crime in any country that guarantees equal protection under the law.  Many were not provided with a reason for their arrest until after they were sent to an internment camp, and often not until shortly before they were released when they were forced to ‘confess’ crimes. Several were given a different reason for their arrest at when they were arrested then they were when they were released. Some were never provided with a reason.\r\n\r\nMost of internment camp survivors interviewed by Amnesty International were given one or two ‘reasons’ why they were arrested. The majority of these reasons fit into four very broad categories. The first category includes offenses related to foreign countries. Numerous survivors were arrested for living, travelling, or studying abroad, or for communicating with people abroad. Many were arrested for being ‘connected’ with people who lived, travelled, studied or communicated with people abroad.\r\n\r\nThe second category includes offenses related to unapproved digital software or communications technology. Many survivors were arrested for using or having forbidden software applications on their phones, especially WhatsApp. The third category includes anything related to religion. Several survivors were arrested for reasons related to Islamic beliefs or practice, including working in a mosque, praying, or having a prayer matt, or possessing a picture related to religion.\r\n\r\nThe fourth category includes anything ‘suspicious’ or ‘untrustworthy’ and anything to do with the ‘three evils forces’ of terrorism, extremism, or separatism. Many survivors were arrested for being classified as suspicious or untrustworthy person, or for having a family member who was a suspicious, untrustworthy, or considered to be an extremist, separatist, or terrorist, or for contacts with ‘terrorists’ or unreliable or suspicious people.\r\n\r\nAmnesty International also interviewed survivors who were arrested for having too many children, and therefore violating China’s family planning policies. As well as survivor who was arrested for refusing to work for the government.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors told Amnesty how they had been arrested after getting explicit permission to do the very thing that they were reportedly arrested for. [Pseudonym B3] told Amnesty that he was arrested for travelling domestically, even though he had obtained permission from the appropriate authorities. [Pseudonym C1] told Amnesty that he was arrested twice for travelling – once abroad and once domestically – even though he had gotten permission from the appropriate authorities to do so both times.\r\n<blockquote>“[After I was arrested the second time] I asked the village chief [why I was arrested]. He said: ‘we are doing what we are told. We don’t know why. All people who are travelling abroad go to the camp. You have no right to ask questions. If you ask it will be seen as resistance. It will not be good for you. You will get answers in the camp.’”</blockquote>\r\nAmnesty International also asked the survivors whether they knew why other people who were in the camp with them had had been arrested, including two survivors – [Pseudonym D2] and [Pseudonym X3] -- who, while detained, were asked by officials in their camp to help other inmates fill-in forms where they were required to list their ‘crimes’ [for more on these forms see section X below on ‘self-confession forms’]. The reasons  that survivors provided they knew about were broadly consisted with the four categories mentioned above; however,[Pseudonym D2], who helped [dozens of] people fill in their confession forms, said that the most common reasons she observed was for ‘having multiple household registrations’, which is prohibited under Chinese law.\r\n\r\nMany of the survivors also stated that they believed that people imprisoned for certain reasons were much less likely to be released and, in particular, that those who had been arrested and interned for reasons related to religion were far less likely to be released and far more likely to receive prison sentence (see section X on prison sentences below).\r\n\r\nThe reasons for arrest provided by camp survivors to Amnesty International are consistent with testimonial and documentary evidence gathered by journalists and other human rights investigators. Most significantly, the reasons are broadly consistent two leaked government documents, which together contain government records of over 2300 people who were arrested sent to internment camps in Xinjiang between 2017 and 2019.  The documents – referred to as the ‘Karakax list’ and the ‘Aksu list’, after the prefectures in Xinjiang where the people name in the documents live – contain, among other things, the official reasons why the individuals were arrested and interned.\r\n\r\nThe Aksu list includes government records on over 2000 people who were arrested and interned after being flagged by China’s “Integrated Joint Operations Platform” (IJOP), a big-data collection program that gathers information about people in Xinjiang. The list reveals that ‘suspicious’ behavior often leading to arrest and detention includes regular religious practice, such as reciting the Quran or wearing religious clothing, having more children that permitted by China’s policies, using certain computer software, such as Skype or a virtual private network (VPN), travelling abroad, or travelling domestically without permission, having ‘extremist thoughts’, being untrustworthy, or being young.\r\n\r\nThe Karakax list includes government records on over 300 people. The most common reason for arrest – shared by nearly half of the people – was that they violated China’s birth control policies. A scholarly analysis reasons revealed that they fall broadly into eight non mutually exclusive categories, which include, untrustworthiness, ‘religion-related’, and ‘anything abroad’.'),
