('1639', '38', 'title_ml_text_english', 'Torture and Other Ill-treatment in Detention'),
('1640', '38', '_title_ml_text_english', 'field_5edfa7bf9ba7d'),
('1641', '38', 'title_ml_text_chinese', ''),
('1642', '38', '_title_ml_text_chinese', 'field_5edfa7989ba7c'),
('1643', '38', 'title_ml_text_uyghur', ''),
('1644', '38', '_title_ml_text_uyghur', 'field_602658467ef5f'),
('1645', '38', 'title_ml_text', ''),
('1646', '38', '_title_ml_text', 'field_5edfa76c9ba7b'),
('1647', '38', 'title', ''),
('1648', '38', '_title', 'field_602657cc293e7'),
('1649', '38', 'content_ml_rich_text_english', 'Every camp survivor interviewed by Amnesty International was tortured or subjected to cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment or punishment (in this report referred to as “torture and other ill-treatment”) during their internment; torture and other ill-treatment are constitutive elements of life in the internment camps.\r\n\r\nThe types of torture and other ill-treatment that detainees experience in the camps generally fall into two broad categories. The first category includes physical torture and ill-treatment that is directed at a specific detainee. This type usually occurs during interrogations or as punishment for ‘misbehavior’ and commonly includes the unlawful use of restraints, such as tiger chains, as well as beatings and electric shocks. The second category includes the physical and psychological torture and other ill-treatment that are experienced by all detainees. This type includes stress positions, sleep deprivation, and various forms of psychological abuse. This type of torture is ubiquitous; the camps are designed to ensure that it is an inescapable aspect of daily life for every detainee.\r\n\r\nPsychological or mental harm can constitute torture. Courts have recognized that there is no necessary physical element to torture. Psychological torture can include isolation, threats, humiliation, sleep deprivation, exposure to light, intimidation deprivation of communication,  exposure to cold, and witnessing others being tortured, intimidation and threats of violence, a restrictive visiting schedule. Attempts to destroy one self-image by removing control over their environment (i.e. Learned helplessness) also torture.\r\n\r\nThe instances of torture and other ill-treatment documented below (and above in section x) are violations of international law. Moreover, collectively, the acts constitute the crime against humanity, of “torture” (see section X below).'),
